---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Hero from '@/components/Hero.astro';
import Breadcrumb from '@/components/Breadcrumb.astro';
import CTA from '@/components/CTA.astro';
import { breadcrumbList } from '@/lib/schema';

const title = 'About AffiliateTools.co — Independent Reviews of Affiliate Marketing Software';
const description = 'AffiliateTools.co is an independent review site covering ad spy tools and the broader software stack affiliate marketers run. Here is who writes these reviews, how we test, and how we handle affiliate relationships.';
const canonical = '/about/';

const jsonLd = [
  breadcrumbList([
    { name: 'Home', path: '/' },
    { name: 'About', path: '/about/' },
  ]),
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical} jsonLd={jsonLd}>
  <section class="container-max" style="padding: 1.5rem 1.25rem 0;">
    <Breadcrumb items={[{ name: 'Home', href: '/' }, { name: 'About' }]} />
  </section>

  <Hero
    eyebrow="About AffiliateTools.co"
    title="Honest reviews of the software affiliate marketers actually run."
    sub="We review ad spy tools, landing-page builders, affiliate networks, and tracking stacks — scored hands-on, published openly, and updated quarterly."
  />

  <article class="container-prose" style="padding: 2rem 1.25rem 4rem;">
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Who we are</h2>
      <p>
        AffiliateTools.co is an independent review site covering the software that affiliate marketers and media buyers actually run. Our editorial team is a small group of affiliate operators, media buyers, and performance-marketing writers. We test tools the way we use them — against real offers, real campaigns, real budgets — and document the scoring criteria openly so readers can judge whether any given ranking fits their workflow.
      </p>
      <p>
        Our editorial framing is simple: <strong>we're affiliate marketers first</strong>. We know the difference between a ClickBank creative and a DTC e-commerce ad. We know why days-running matters more than impressions for CPA research. And we know when a tool is genuinely useful versus when it's just marketing the category.
      </p>

      <h2>Why we started</h2>
      <p>
        Affiliate marketers couldn't find honest tool reviews. Every other site in this category fell into one of two buckets: pay-for-play listicles where every tool is "the best," or thinly-disguised marketing funnels with no real testing. Both failure modes produce the same useless outcome for the buyer.
      </p>
      <p>
        We built the site we wished existed. AffiliateTools.co ships with in-depth reviews, head-to-head comparisons, buyer-intent pages, and ranked listicles covering the queries affiliate marketers actually search — "adspy alternatives," "best ad spy tools for ClickBank," "best free ad spy tool," and dozens more. Every price is dated. Every marketing claim is attributed. Every listicle rankings is reproducible from the scoring rubric.
      </p>

      <h2>How we handle affiliate relationships</h2>
      <p>
        Some links on AffiliateTools.co are affiliate links. If you sign up for a tool through one of those links, we may earn a commission at no extra cost to you. This is how the site is funded — same as nearly every review site on the internet.
      </p>
      <p>
        We take affiliate-link integrity seriously and enforce three rules:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>No pay-to-rank.</strong> A tool cannot pay to be included in a listicle, cannot pay to be moved up a ranking, and cannot pay to have a negative verdict softened. Rankings come from the scoring rubric, not commercial relationships.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Open methodology.</strong> Our <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a> documents the eight dimensions we score each tool on, how we weight those dimensions for different listicle intents, and how we verify competitor pricing. You can audit our work and reproduce our rankings.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Balanced verdicts.</strong> Every review states what each tool does badly alongside what it does well. We won't recommend a tool for a use case it doesn't fit — even if we have an affiliate relationship with it. For example, the TikTok ad spy tools listicle recommends <a href="/ad-spy-tools/pipiads-review/">PiPiADS</a>; the dropshipping listicle recommends <a href="/ad-spy-tools/minea-review/">Minea</a>; the free-tier listicle recommends <a href="/ad-spy-tools/bigspy-review/">BigSpy</a>.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2>What we review</h2>
      <p>
        Today: <strong>ad spy and ad intelligence tools</strong>. Seven tools in depth — AdRecon, AdSpy, BigSpy, PowerAdSpy, Foreplay, Minea, PiPiADS — plus head-to-head comparisons and ranked listicles covering the queries affiliate marketers actually search for.
      </p>
      <p>
        Planned next 12 months:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Landing page builders</strong> — ClickFunnels, Systeme.io, Leadpages, Unbounce, Instapage, scored against affiliate marketer use cases.</li>
        <li><strong>Affiliate networks</strong> — ClickBank, Digistore24, BuyGoods, MaxWeb, WarriorPlus, MoreNiche, and regional networks.</li>
        <li><strong>Tracking platforms</strong> — Voluum, RedTrack, Binom, FunnelFlux, ClickMagick, Everflow.</li>
        <li><strong>Email marketing tools</strong> — Beehiiv, ConvertKit, Klaviyo, targeted at affiliate email monetization.</li>
        <li><strong>CRO tools</strong> — heat maps, session recording, A/B testing for affiliate funnels.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        If you're an affiliate operator with strong opinions on what we should cover next, email us.
      </p>

      <h2>Editorial policies</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Affiliate links.</strong> Some links on the site are affiliate links — labeled with <code>rel="sponsored"</code> on the anchor. Affiliate relationships are disclosed on the <a href="/disclosure/">editorial disclosure page</a>.</li>
        <li><strong>Paid placements.</strong> We do not accept paid rankings or sponsored "best of" placements. Tools are not removable from listicles in exchange for payment.</li>
        <li><strong>Corrections.</strong> Email <a href="mailto:hello@affiliatetools.co">hello@affiliatetools.co</a> with corrections. We publish corrections openly — no silent edits.</li>
        <li><strong>Fact verification.</strong> Pricing is verified quarterly. Feature claims are verified annually. Every page shows the "Updated" date in the hero.</li>
        <li><strong>Competitor claims.</strong> Marketing claims made by tool vendors (e.g., "200M+ ads indexed") are cited as claims, never stated as facts.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How to reach us</h2>
      <p>
        The fastest way to reach us is email: <a href="mailto:hello@affiliatetools.co">hello@affiliatetools.co</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        For corrections, pricing updates, partnership inquiries, or tip-offs about something we missed, use the same address. See the <a href="/contact/">contact page</a> for which channel to use for what.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <CTA
    variant="footer"
    campaign="about"
    medium="about"
    label="Try AdRecon — $299 lifetime"
    kicker="Our top pick for Meta affiliate research"
    body="Our highest-scoring ad spy tool for Meta affiliates: 300,000+ records, Landing Page Ripper, and affiliate-network classification. $299 lifetime as of April 2026."
  />
</BaseLayout>
